John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scotland's independent schools continue to be distinguished by academic excellence, which continued in 2018 with further outstanding examination results, and is only further underpinned by individual and joint successes in sport, the arts, music and other community initiatives.
With over 30,000 pupils from all over Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest possible level of care for their pupils and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their pupils for further and higher education, the profession of their choice and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored curriculum, we see that modern languages are still popular and sought after as electives in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you speak to someone in a language they understand, you reach their head".
If you speak to him in his own language, you will reach his heart.
This is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
The current results of this year show that languages with the highest pass rates are at the top of the rankings of independent schools.
A total of 68 per cent of pupils who studied foreign languages scored A on the higher examinations.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students in Mandarin scored A's in the higher examinations, while 72 percent of students learning German, 69 percent of students learning French, and 63 percent of students learning Spanish also scored A's.
This illustrates that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as an important skill which children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages are now considered as electives as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and elsewhere.
According to a 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills, 17 per cent of the reasons employers cited for problems filling vacancies were related to a lack of language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly essential in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more job openings require languages, this knowledge is essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the profession chosen, young people who have learned a second language will have a real advantage in the future from such a lifelong skill.
Being able to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically give multilinguals an edge over competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the United Kingdom, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15 percent).
That's why it's important for today's children that we invest now in language teaching.
Children who speak several languages, especially languages from developing countries, will have a better chance of finding meaningful employment.
In Scotland, all schools teach different languages.
A number of schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages considered to be the most important for the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Wherever your child's interests lie, independent schools will always have a range of languages with a suitable range of specialised teachers.
Scottish independent schools are committed to creating a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future may hold.
At this point in a global economic environment, it cannot be denied that languages are still of fundamental importance for the future of the country.
In fact, modern languages should be considered as international communication capability.
Independent schools will continue to offer young people in Scotland this choice, diversity and excellence.
It's got to be fair.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
