North Korea rejects unilateral disarmament without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions deepened its mistrust of the United States and that under these circumstances the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN's annual general assembly that North Korea had taken "significant measures" last year in good faith, such as halting nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and pledging not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technologies.
"We do not see a corresponding reaction from the US", he said.
"Without confidence in the United States, there is no confidence in our national security, and under these circumstances, we will not unilaterally disarm first".
While Ri repeated familiar North Korean complaints about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded for successive steps, his statement seemed significant in that it did not reject unilateral denuclearization from the outset, as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong-un and Donald Trump at the first summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, in which Kim had promised to work towards the "denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula", while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, while the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
In addition, Washington is resisting calls for an easing of the severe international sanctions against North Korea.
"The US insists on denuclearization first and is increasing pressure through sanctions to achieve its goal through force, and is even against declaring the end of the war", Ri said.
The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a brainchild of people who know nothing about us.
The problem is that the continued sanctions are deepening our suspicions.
Ri did not discuss plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US head of state had highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, adding: 'If South Korea had been the other party to the denuclearization issue, instead of the US, this stalemate would not have been reached in the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula.'
Yet the tone of Ri's speech was vastly different from his speech last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to target the US mainland with North Korean missiles after the evil President Trump called Kim a "missile man" on a suicide mission.
This year, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, praised Kim at the United Nations for his courage in taking disarmament steps, but said there was still much work to be done and sanctions would have to remain in place until North Korea denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no time frame for this: "Whether it takes two years, three years or five months doesn't matter".
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday: "The enforcement of the Security Council's sanctions must in any case be vigorously continued until we achieve complete, final and verified denuclearization".
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to financially dry up Pyongyang's nuclear weapons and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was unsuccessful.
In July, on leaving Pyongyang, he said progress had been made, only to be accused by North Korea hours later of making "gang-like" demands.
North Korea promised at a meeting with Moon this month to dismantle a missile base and a nuclear complex if the United States took "appropriate action".
He said Kim told him that the "appropriate measures" he was seeking were security guarantees Trump had given in Singapore, as well as steps to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard students learn in a course to get enough sleep
A new course at Harvard University is making sure all undergraduates get more sleep this year, a measure against the growing machismo culture of staying awake with caffeine and studying all night.
One scientist has found that students at the world's leading university often lack self-care.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, and he believes it is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after giving a talk about the effects of sleep deprivation on learning.
"At the end, a girl came to me and asked, 'Why am I only learning about this now, in my last year?'
"I was surprised", he told The Telegraph.
This year's first course taught students how the basics of good sleep contribute to academic and athletic performance and to overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university's health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after noticing that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one section, students see a picture of a room in a residential home and click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise shoes and books, which provide information on the effects of caffeine and light, the effects of sleep deprivation on athletic performance and the importance of a sleep routine.
In another section, participants learn that long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, and cancer.
Then, with the help of a map of the university campus, which includes interactive symbols, they are encouraged to reflect on their daily routine.
We know it's not going to change student behavior immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know this  just as you have a right to know how your choice to smoke affects your health, Professor Czeisler added.
Pride in "sending night shifts" is still prevalent, he said, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students are making sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Ensuring adequate sleep should be the "secret weapon" of all students against stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said, and weight gain can be avoided, since sleep deprivation puts the brain in hunger mode, causing them to be hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemistry and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design the course, having taken one of his courses last year in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and motivated him to push for a university-wide course.
He hopes that in the next step all postgraduate students will be encouraged to complete a similar programme of study before they start their studies at the competitive university.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set up a wake-up and bedtime alarm and be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can disturb circadian rhythms and lead to problems falling asleep.
