New research is being conducted at a farm in the Scottish Highlands to show how bats use the landscape to search for food.
It is hoped that the results will provide further insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help guide future conservation efforts.
The study, carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland, will track midget and mosquito bats, as well as brown-eared long-eared bats and water bats at Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key locations on the property to record the bat's activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile tests with portable detectors.
A sound analysis of all the recordings by experts determines the frequency of the bats' calls and determines which species is doing what.
A map and habitat report are then produced to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour at the landscape level.
Rob Dewar, conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas of the habitat are most important to bats and how they are used by each species.
This data will help to identify the benefits of habitat management measures such as grassland creation and show how to preserve forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have declined significantly over the last century.
They are threatened by construction and development work which affects sleeping places and leads to habitat loss.
Windmills and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly traps and the chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey because of their nocturnal hunting habits.
They use sophisticated echo-tracing to detect insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the upkeep of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland, takes the bat issue very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts who regularly conduct investigations, sleeping places inspections and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up Scotland's first and only bat sanctuary at Threave Estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
Landlord David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal living space for them.
"Here in Threave we have a great bat area", he explains.
We have the old buildings, lots of old trees and a great habitat.
But there is much we don't know about bats, so we are doing this work here and at other properties that will help us learn more about what bats need to feel comfortable.
It stresses the importance of first eliminating the presence of bats before maintenance work on the holdings, as the accidental destruction of a single nesting site could kill up to 400 females and young and wipe out the entire population on site.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or destroy them or their nesting sites.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official with the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She explains: "We still have a lot to learn about bats, and we don't know the status of many of our species' populations".
